  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

", viewStyles: [ 'completion.css' ], scripts: [ 'completion.js' ] } ], initialised: '2019/07/03 05:31:04.0102' }, studyConfig: { studyName: '20190703-phonsimilarity01', completionCode: 'O242CA76', redirectTimer: '30000', completionURL: 'https://app.prolific.ac/submissions/complete?cc=O242CA76', studybackgroundColor: 'Black', studyTextColor: 'White', consentCopy: '
  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.

  • What is the study about?

This study, “Short Term Memory and the Immediate Serial Recall Task” looks at Verbal Short Term Memory and examines how well current models of memory explain recall of lists of words.

  • Who is carrying out the study?

Steven Roodenrys, an academic staff member in the School of Psychology

  • What does the study involve?

The study asks you to read multiple lists of words  and then recall each list in order of its presentation by typing them into the computer.

  • Who will see the study results?

Your responses will be recorded electronically. Only the researcher will have access to results. These results will not be identifiable by name.

Electronic responses will be coded by a number.  Electronic results will then be kept in locked data files.

  • How much time does the study take?

This study will take approximately 20 minutes to complete. However, times will vary according to the individual.

  • Can I withdraw from this study?

Being in this study is completely voluntary – you are not under any obligation to consent and if you do consent you can withdraw at any time without affecting your relationship with University of Wollongong. However, as your data is not identifiable it may not be possible to withdraw your data once you have completed the study.

  • Will this study benefit me?

You will be given a full explanation of the study as the end of the experiment, so the benefit to you will be in an improved understanding of one area of cognitive psychology and the research methods used to investigate cognitive processes.

  • Can I tell other people about the study?

Yes

  • What if I require information about the study or my involvement in it?

When you have read this information Steven Roodenrys can discuss it with you further and answer any questions you may have.

  • What if I have a complaint or any concerns? Any person with complaints or concerns about the conduct of a research study can contact

If you have any enquiries about the research, you can contact Steven Roodenrys (ph. (02) 4421 4072) or if you have any concerns or complaints regarding the way the research is or has been conducted, you can contact the Ethics Officer, Human Research Ethics Committee, Office of Research, University of Wollongong on 4221 3386 or email rso-ethics@uow.edu.au.

', instructionCopy: '

You will be presented with lists of 6 words on the screen, one word at a time. At the end of each list your task is to recall the list by typing the words intot he response box in the same order as they appeared in.  If you cannot recall an item you can hit "enter" and leave it blank.
You will be presented with 2 practice lists and then 20 experimental lists.
